  }, {
    "href": "https://readwise.io/to_kindle?action=open&asin=B06WVYW33Y&location=1766"
  }), "Location\xA01766"), ")"), mdx("p", null, "If you focus your time and energy on understanding, you cannot help but learn. But if you focus your time and energy on learning without trying to understand, you will not only not understand, but also probably not learn. And the effects are cumulative. There is a reason why the best scientists are also often very good teachers. For someone like Richard Feynman, everything was about understanding, regardless of whether he was doing research or teaching. His famous Feynman diagrams are primarily tools to make understanding easier and his lectures are famous because they help students to really understand physics. It is not surprising, therefore, that he was passionate about challenging traditional education methods. He couldn\u2019t stand textbooks full of pseudo-explanations (Feynman 1985) and teachers who tried to make learning easier for students by using artificial \u201Creal-life\u201D examples instead of using their actual prior understanding as a connection point (Feynman 1963). (", mdx("a", _extends({
    parentName: "p"
  }, {
    "href": "https://readwise.io/to_kindle?action=open&asin=B06WVYW33Y&location=1930"
  }), "Location\xA01930"), ")"), mdx("p", null, "overview of it. On the contrary, we are much better off accepting as early as possible that an overview of the slip-box is as impossible as having an overview of our own thinking while we are thinking. As an extension of our own memory, the slip-box is the medium we think in, not something we think about. (", mdx("a", _extends({
